The paper proposes a new training scheme for deep neural networks, which is relevant to several sub-fields of computer science. The focus on improving generalization ability suggests that the paper is likely to belong to the machine learning (cs.LG) or computer vision (cs.CV) sub-categories. The use of different loss functions and the emphasis on optimization also suggest that the paper may be relevant to artificial intelligence (cs.AI) and neural networks (cs.NE). Finally, the experiments on Residual Networks and DenseNet suggest that the paper may also be relevant to natural language processing (cs.CL).
